<li id="cite_note-austlii-1">^ <a href="#cite_ref-austlii_1-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-austlii_1-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="http://austlii.edu.au" class="external free" title="http://austlii.edu.au" rel="nofollow">http://austlii.edu.au</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-2"><b><a href="#cite_ref-2" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://online.ceb.com/CalCases/C2/59C2d57.htm" class="external text" title="http://online.ceb.com/CalCases/C2/59C2d57.htm" rel="nofollow">Greenman v. Yuba Power Products, Inc. (1963) 59 C2d 57</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-3"><b><a href="#cite_ref-3" title="">^</a></b> <i>Schmier v. Supreme Court</i>, <a href="http://online.ceb.com/calcases/CA4/78CA4t703.htm" class="external text" title="http://online.ceb.com/calcases/CA4/78CA4t703.htm" rel="nofollow">78 Cal. App. 4th 703</a> (2000). The plaintiff in this case unsuccessfully challenged the selective publication policy as unconstitutional. The court retorted: "Appellant either misunderstands or ignores the realities of the intermediate appellate process." The court went on to describe the variety of frivolous appeals regularly encountered by the Courts of Appeal, and concluded: "Our typical opinions in such cases add nothing to the body of stare decisis, and if published would merely clutter overcrowded library shelves and databases with information utterly useless to anyone other than the actual litigants therein and complicate the search for meaningful precedent."</li>
<li id="cite_note-4"><b><a href="#cite_ref-4" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web"><a href="http://kyrules.west.thomson.com/Find/Default.wl?DocName=KYSTRCPR76%2E28&amp;FindType=W&amp;DB=KY-TOC-WEB%3BSTAKYTOC&amp;RS=WLW2%2E07&amp;VR=2%2E0" class="external text" title="http://kyrules.west.thomson.com/Find/Default.wl?DocName=KYSTRCPR76%2E28&amp;FindType=W&amp;DB=KY-TOC-WEB%3BSTAKYTOC&amp;RS=WLW2%2E07&amp;VR=2%2E0" rel="nofollow">"CR 76.28(4)"</a>. <i>Kentucky Rules of Civil Procedure</i>. Kentucky Court of Justice<span class="printonly">. <a href="http://kyrules.west.thomson.com/Find/Default.wl?DocName=KYSTRCPR76%2E28&amp;FindType=W&amp;DB=KY-TOC-WEB%3BSTAKYTOC&amp;RS=WLW2%2E07&amp;VR=2%2E0" class="external free" title="http://kyrules.west.thomson.com/Find/Default.wl?DocName=KYSTRCPR76%2E28&amp;FindType=W&amp;DB=KY-TOC-WEB%3BSTAKYTOC&amp;RS=WLW2%2E07&amp;VR=2%2E0" rel="nofollow">http://kyrules.west.thomson.com/Find/Default.wl?DocName=KYSTRCPR76%2E28&amp;FindType=W&amp;DB=KY-TOC-WEB%3BSTAKYTOC&amp;RS=WLW2%2E07&amp;VR=2%2E0</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2008-04-12</span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=CR+76.28%284%29&amp;rft.atitle=Kentucky+Rules+of+Civil+Procedure&amp;rft.pub=Kentucky+Court+of+Justice&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fkyrules.west.thomson.com%2FFind%2FDefault.wl%3FDocName%3DKYSTRCPR76%252E28%26FindType%3DW%26DB%3DKY-TOC-WEB%253BSTAKYTOC%26RS%3DWLW2%252E07%26VR%3D2%252E0&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Case_citation"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
